Welcome to my SVG CV!

Hi there - I'm SVG me! Thanks so much for considering my Founders & Coders application. I hope you enjoy reading it as much as I enjoyed making it!

Why did I make this website?

I wanted to make my CV more exciting. I also wanted to build a responsive website from scratch (my 2018 New Year's resolution!). Turning my CV into an interactive website seemed like a great way to accomplish both goals and practice useful web development skills.

Why did I use SVG?

I watched a web series called Everything You Need to Know About SVG. The course compares SVG with other graphic types and covers ways to use SVG to build brilliant websites. I was amazed by how SVG seemed to make it so simple to scale and manipulate images with CSS. I wanted to give it a go, so I set myself a challenge to make a one-page website using SVG for all the images. Aside from a PNG here and a GIF there, everything is SVG.

Why did I start coding?

The Pudding. Thats the website that got me keen on coding. If you dont know, The Pudding is a news site run by a small team of 'journalist-engineers' who publish stories about complex topics using original datasets, primary research, and interactivity. The first one I read back in 2014 was about the size of different rappers vocabularies, and it blew my mind. I emailed the author, Matt Daniels, to ask him how he made it.

He said it was the kind of story he couldn't have done before the Internet. From the APIs and web crawlers that sifted through thousands of song lyrics pages on Genius.com to the interactive data visualisation library (D3.js) he used to present the findings, everything about it relied on web technologies.

I was curious to learn more. The problem was, I was also struggling to pass third year law.

The 'more' would have to wait.

Three years, one graduation, and a boatload of onion bhajis later (TL;DR - I went to India), I landed a job writing for a website where I got to grips with basic HTML. I also started going to coding meetups (Journocoders, Codebar) where I met some great people who inspired and encouraged me to learn how to code.

Coding had always seemed suspiciously like magic to me. So, you can imagine how I felt when, at 7:32pm on 24 December 2017, I saw the words Hello world! materialise on my Macbook command line.

CLICK TO TEAR

I was hooked. I wanted to learn how to develop for the web and code cool, interactive web experiences like Matt Daniels rap vocabularies piece. Weirdly enough, things came full circle this year when my idea for a research project about popular musicians per lyric earnings got picked up at work. I wrote a simple Python web scraper, used it to gather the data, and found a story somewhere in the mix. Feel free to read my write up!

Why Founders and Coders?

Im grateful to have received these opportunities. I wouldnt have been able to attend university or visit other countries without financial assistance, and I wouldnt have started coding without support from friends and family. Im always reminded of the story, depicted in this video, of people feeding each other with spoons that are too long to feed themselves. I do agree that helping others is more rewarding (in every way) than focusing solely on ourselves.

So I found myself nodding along to a lot of what I heard at the FAC open evening in October. I agree with the ethos of helping people from all kinds of backgrounds to grow and develop. And I like the idea that student projects can potentially be of use to real charities. I also found it reassuring to hear that its possible to run a coding bootcamp on reciprocal giving instead of high tuition fees.

But the part that excited me the most was the emphasis on peer learning and paired coding. When I was a teaching assistant, I used to get my students to brainstorm problems in pairs before opening up discussions to the class. I think its a great way to learn because you feel more confident airing your ideas to a group after vetting them with a partner, and because it exposes you to perspectives you wouldnt have come across on your own. Which is why, every FAC meetup I go to, I'm confident I'll learn something new from someone I never knew.

All in all, if the course is anything like the Monday meetups, I think I will get a lot out of it. While Ive thoroughly enjoyed completing the course prerequisites, it has been a slog at times. But no matter how stuck I get, I always look forward to the Monday meetups, if nothing else because 149 Fonthill Road is full of like-minded people to vent with and sturdy desks to bash my head against when freeCodeCamp refuses to save my challenge submissions.
